    <!-- SCIENCE DEEP DIVE -->
    <h2 id="science">Reishi vs. Other Mushrooms for Anxiety: What Research Shows</h2>

    <p>Not all functional mushrooms are created equal for anxiety management. While the adaptogenic mushroom category is broad, each species has distinct bioactive compounds that target different health outcomes. Understanding these differences is essential for choosing the right product for anxiety specifically.</p>

    <div class="vs-strip">
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Reishi (Ganoderma lucidum)</strong>
        <p>Primary anxiolytic mushroom. Triterpenes modulate GABA-A receptors; beta-glucans reduce neuroinflammation. Strongest evidence for direct anxiety reduction.<br /><em>Best for: Anxiety, stress, sleep quality</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Lion's Mane (Hericium erinaceus)</strong>
        <p>Stimulates NGF (nerve growth factor) for neuroplasticity and cognitive function. Anxiety benefits are secondary to cognitive effects.<br /><em>Best for: Focus, memory, brain fog with mild anxiety</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Cordyceps (Cordyceps militaris)</strong>
        <p>Enhances ATP production and oxygen utilization. Primary benefits are energy and endurance, not calming.<br /><em>Best for: Energy, stamina, athletic performance</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Chaga (Inonotus obliquus)</strong>
        <p>Powerful antioxidant with high ORAC score. Supports immune function and reduces oxidative stress but limited direct anxiolytic data.<br /><em>Best for: Immune support, antioxidant defense</em></p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- HOW TO CHOOSE -->
    <h2 id="how-to-choose">How to Choose the Right Mushroom Gummy for Anxiety</h2>

    <p>The mushroom supplement market is flooded with products that vary dramatically in potency, sourcing, and formulation quality. These are the criteria that separate effective anxiety-targeted mushroom gummies from ineffective ones:</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>1. Fruiting body vs. mycelium</strong>
        <p>Triterpenes are concentrated in the fruiting body. Mycelium grown on grain contains more starch (alpha-glucans) than bioactive compounds. For anxiety, fruiting body extract is significantly more effective milligram for milligram.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>2. Extraction method</strong>
        <p>Dual extraction (hot water + alcohol) captures both beta-glucans and triterpenes. Single extraction misses one category of bioactives. For anxiety, triterpene extraction via alcohol is essential.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>3. Dose threshold</strong>
        <p>Clinical studies show effects at 1,000-3,000mg/day. Products delivering under 500mg per serving may require multiple daily servings to reach therapeutic range. Check the per-serving dose, not just the bottle claim.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>4. Synergistic ingredients</strong>
        <p>L-theanine, ashwagandha, lemon balm, and passionflower all have independent anxiolytic evidence. Products combining reishi with one or more of these compounds can produce faster and more pronounced calming effects.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

